('1213', 'departed', '逝', '<img src=\"E9809D.png\" />', 'departed, fold, finger, fingers, axe, road', '10', '31', 'One of the dearest of Japan´s dearly departed is Sasaki Sadako, who developed Leukemia after the bombing of Hiroshima, and became famous for folding more than a thousand paper cranes, never giving up hope. To this day, people in Hiroshima still fold origami cranes in her memory. For this character, let us imagine a parade in her honor, the entire road lined with folded cranes.', 'JH', '1', 'セイ', 'ゆ.く、い.く', NULL, NULL),
('1214', 'vow', '誓', '<img src=\"E8AA93.png\" />', 'vow, fold, finger, fingers, axe, say, words, keitai, mouth', '14', '31', 'This Japanese couple wrote the vows that they had made to each other onto a piece of paper and then folded it into an origami, and put it somewhere in their appartment. To everybody else it is an origami, but to them it is also a symbol of their vows. -- \"the folded words are vows\". Note : in this story and a few others I use the image of an origami for the primitive \"fold\".', 'JH', '1', 'セイ', 'ちか.う', NULL, NULL),
